This is a Next.js SSR scaffold with an explicit Node server wrapper for production startup.

Use this when you want Next app-router features while keeping startup contract explicit as a Node entrypoint.

Dev mode:

```bash
pnpm run dev:ssr
```

Local workspace TypeScript dependencies update in the same dev session when they are workspace-linked (`workspace:`, `link:`, or `file:`) and imported from app code used by client or SSR render paths.

Generated module manifests and loaders:

- generated contracts in `buck-out/tmp/module-contracts/<app-id>/`
- generated runtime manifest projection in `app/` (derived from canonical contracts)
- loader surfaces in `app/wasm-contract.ts` and `app/ts-modules.ts`
- server parity helpers: `server/wasm-contract.ts` and `server/ts-modules.ts`
- consume through module-key APIs only

Production build and startup:

```bash
pnpm run build:ssr
pnpm run start:ssr
```

Server-side Wasm contract artifact:

```text
dist/server/wasm-contract/top.wasm
```

Local dependency troubleshooting:

- If local dependency edits do not apply, verify `next.config.mjs` includes `transpilePackages` entries for workspace-linked dependency package names.
- If local dependency source resolves outside the app root, verify `next.config.mjs` keeps `experimental.externalDir = true`.
- If local dependency edits stay stale after `package.json` changes, restart `pnpm run dev:ssr`.
- If producer edits do not update wasm output, check `app/wasm-producer/payload.txt`, then run `pnpm run dev:wasm:watch` and verify `[wasm-watch] sync:ok`.
- `pnpm run dev:wasm:watch` syncs generated contracts into `buck-out/tmp/module-contracts/<app-id>/` and loads manifests from that path.
- If server-rendered wasm probes fail in dev, confirm generated assets exist under `app/wasm-contract/` and rerun the logged watcher recovery command.
- For deterministic Phase 3 checks, run repeated client/server/wasm edit cycles in one `dev:ssr` session and verify process PID stays stable.
- If updates appear stalled, check for a recent `[wasm-watch] rebuild:start` without a matching `sync:ok` or `rebuild:fail`, then run the logged recovery command.
- If startup appears blocked, verify `/` responds on `http://127.0.0.1:${PORT:-4173}` before making edits.
